rComments: idk why people like him so much he's so unorganized and his tangents take up wayy too much time. you'll be on week 9 and still talking about lecture 6.....

AMAZING PROF :') hands down my favourite prof at uoft.. absolutely loved loved loved his lectures and he's just the best.. he goes off on tangents sometimes but it's extremely interesting. honestly i just loved him!! I wish he taught more classes :'(

This class is proof of the brain's ability to adapt to different environments. There are no slides. No notes. Barely a syllabus. Professor reads off a word document with headlines. Regardless, I love prof jurgensen. His tangents are interesting even though they take up almost half the lecture time. He ends class early. Explains concepts clearly.
teacherRatingTags: ['Tough grader', "Skip class? You won't pass.", 'Lecture heavy']

rComments: I really enjoyed this class, for an intro course its very interesting. He needs to use slides rather than his messy notes and goes on tangents. Going to lecture is not necessary but reading the textbooks is. Overall, easy to get a good grade.
awesome prof though he loves his tangents during lectures so you'll fall behind a bit but its fine. explains everything nicely and always has a recap in the beginning incase you miss class

Has a tendency to really go on a tangent during lectures, especially conspiracy theories. Which is very entertaining, and means that if you read the textbook, you'll do relatively fine on the tests. Grades tend to depend on how hard your TA marks.

Overall great professor and I really enjoyed his class. He does have a tendency to go on tangents at times but his lectures are always very interesting. One thing I will say is that his instructions for essays could be a bit unclear. Tests were very fair and straightforward.
I had him for POL208 as well as POL326. Nice guy, I'm glad he was my professor. Yes, perhaps he should have lecture slides. But overall, good prof

Jurgensens lectures wander around and can be hard to follow. He doesnt have slides and instead projects very minimal bullet points on a Word doc in front of the class. Because he wanders off-topic so often, hes never able to cover all his content in one class. He seems like a nice guy, but hes just not very organized.
Lecture heavy, but a good lecturer. Often goes off on tangents and seems disorganized, but its a good experience overall. Just paying attention is enough, no textbook required.
A good prof. Had him for 208 and 326. No lecture slides, but still easy to follow if you pay attention.

I took POL326 in summer and Prof Jurgensen was amazing. He makes the rather dry and tough material understandable and interesting. He tries to fit a lot in his lectures and sometimes goes off tangent but I still find this course enjoyable. Make sure to go to every lecture and take good notes. His tests are straightforward, no surprises.
teacherRatingTags: ['Lecture heavy', "Skip class? You won't pass.", 'Graded by few things']

rComments: He makes US Foreign Policy very interesting. He's very knowledgeable (especially on China) and lectures flawlessly. He should've spent more time on the Middle East. I don't know why he isn't appointed professor. He's always respectful and responds to emails ASAP.

He's an able lecturer who knows his stuff and always seeks to answer questions. The essay and final were straightforward with no surprises. His lectures can be dry because he teaches the political economy content in 208 and doesn't use visual aids when talking - but otherwise, he's a good prof
Prof Jurgensen is a national treasure, best prof ever in every regard.

He is a good professor but hes lectures were boring yet helpful at the same time. His lectures, assignment and exams were detailed and straightforward. The exams are essay questions only. It's an easy course as long as you do the work assigned, attended the lectures (made notes), and participated in the tutorials. Tutorials are mandatory.
teacherRatingTags: ['Lecture heavy', 'Graded by few things', 'Accessible outside class']

rComments: One of the best professors I had in my life. He respected every student in the class, and the example he gave were very detailed. I just love his lecture. His lectures had so many materials, and he talks so fast, so be prepared to take a lot of notes. However, the lectures were not hard to understand. (English is not my first language)
A highly knowledgeable prof. His lectures may seem like ramblings, but they are full of interesting stories. Do the readings and attend tutorials.

His lectures are really good and intense. I found that only attending lectures and listening to him for 2 hours can easily get you a 70-80. A lot of people complain that he talks fast but it's important given the content of the course. The course itself is pretty easy given you keep up with current events, news and have slight common sense. Easy A.
The midterm and exam are based mainly on the lectures, so make sure to attend and take lots of notes.
teacherRatingTags: ['Tough grader', 'Graded by few things', "Skip class? You won't pass."]

rComments: incredibly dry lectures, wouldn't recommend
Professor Jurgensen is great! Very great lecturer, and seems like a very nice person in general.

JÃ¼rgensen's one of the reasons I chose to specialize in Polisci! He's a great professor; his tests are so easy. I just didn't like the exam questions. But everything else was great. He's so passionate and optimistic about what he teaches. If doing any intl. politics course and have him as a prof, you're in for a good ride
He is the best professor I ever had so far. Lecture's are ok, but its worth it.
Loved him! Went off sometimes but always interesting and easy to follow
teacherRatingTags: ['Amazing lectures', 'Clear grading criteria', "Skip class? You won't pass."]

rComments: goes on very interesting tangents. would recommend :)
Hardest lecture I've had to sit through. Its very dry and he's very vague when answering questions.
he's hard to follow because he's monotonous and his lecture slides are not very informative.

Jurgensen was a good professor in terms of teaching, but a really strict person outside the classroom. He gives 1 hour tests so you basically have to rush through, and the marking for the essays was really strict. I'm avoiding him for the rest of my UofT life!
Great--albeit v. left leaning-- professor. Textbook (FLZ) is awesome. Tests are easy and tutorials are fun. Enjoy!

Overall, prof. Jurgensen is very jolly & sweet. However, he does ramble off topic during lecture (course was 3 weeks behind at one point), and his tests have a very short time limit (1 hour for 4 identifications + essay).
I really like the professor. He made the class interesting. Each lecture is like hearing a story. That said I skipped several lectures and did fine.

I really like this class! Professor's Jurgensen lectures are very clear and breathtaking. I also found another very important criteria that he replies to the emails shortly which is very helpful for the students.

Jurgensen is really knowledgeable and passionate about course material. Tends to fall behind the syllabus schedule but he adjusts the exams to reflect that. He uses a lot of real world examples when explaining theoretical concepts to make lectures more interesting. Doesn't use lecture slides or blackboard much.

Excellent professor. Jurgensen talks in a strange brisk manner but he is VERY informative, VERY clear and he manages to draw nuances and perspectives in a concise manner. The tests were also easy if you give a bit of thought to the material.

One of my favourite professors during undergrad. Has a unique speaking style - rapid but clear - which seems to bore some & engage others (like me). Definitely gained a lot more knowledge and understanding from his class than on average. Explains foreign policy in a way that is understandable to the uninitiated while still interesting.

A fair grader and was very knowledgable about current American affairs. Typical classes involved a discussion of a current topic trending in foreign policy followed by a more general discussion of the history of American foreign policy.
Pay attention in class & do the readings. He is helpful with concepts from readings as well.

A very approachable Prof, and is very open-minded about the differing opinions during lecture discussions. His lectures are very dry though, speaks a little fast so its hard to keep up if you zone out for a second, and doesn't give breaks in between so prepare to bring coffee!
Amazing Professor, best teaching style.
SUFFICE TO SAY you will love this class.

excellent lecturer with an astonishing depth of knowledge about political history and current affairs. he talks a lot about contemporary issues and has the ability to make even the most nebulous narratives make sense in five minutes. very approachable, very friendly, presents material in unbiased manner but also not afraid to give his own opinion.
i found him to be incredibly knowledgeable and very approachable. My only criticism is his lecturing. The content is interesting but his style is dry and boring.
Love love love, he is soooo sweet and helpful!

Loved him, I would definitely take more of his courses. His lectures are engaging and interesting. He is very old fashioned and never uses portal or any other kind of electronics. Exams questions are taken from past exams (on library website) and are identical. Overall great prof and course !
This is one of the best classes I've ever taken, prof is really, really, really helpful, goes out of his way to help students. The material is interesting and the prof is engaging.

Very knowledgeable in U.S Foreign Policy. This is not always the best thing, however, as he tends to drone on about a certain topic which detracts from the overall lecture scheduling. Methods of evaluation - ID's/Essays- were fair. Tended to provide broad overview of topics. Course could have had a more narrowed  focus in the 2nd half

Goes very into detail which is the one thing that causes him to fall back on the lesson plan but always a gives a great lecture that has students at the edge of their seats. And he's verrrryyy charming
sik

Hate to write a bad review for a nice person, but I thought that a topic as interesting as US foreign policy was wasted in this class...could have been way more interesting. Expectations of paper were too vague and exam questions did not really align with his lectures.
HOT.
Makes you look forward to coming to lectures because his lectures are really interesting and communicates things in a way you can understand. Love that he doesn't present a bias when he lectures.

Absolutely insightful and so learned. His ability to present various views without personal bias is extremely admirable. Although he tends to repeat himself,the course is extremely low impact. This man is really really smart and REALLY good looking. His lectures are easy to follow although he does go a bit fast at times, and he is so nice and helpful if you have any questions.

he repeats his lectures, but explains everything crystal clear. His essay tests are super easy if u hv listened to his lectures. rally hot
Excellent lecturer who is extremely knowledgable on U.S foreign policy. His analysis was always sophisticated and penetrating, and went far beyond what typically passes for news in the mainstream.

Good prof, lectures are really interesting. I like how he relates things from a broad range of examples and doesnt conform to the typical ones.  However sometimes hes all over the place, its hard to keep track of exactly what hes talking about as if he has too many ideas and cant articulate them.

This guy is cool - he always tells great stories, keeps the class interested - makes clear what he wants, and explains concepts well...I guess it helps that the course was friggin easy.  Learn the BuzzWords people.
